Dad, what are you doin' here?

244
00:17:00,762 --> 00:17:03,139
I'm robbin' your room,
that's what I'm doin' here.

245
00:17:03,181 --> 00:17:04,933
We drive 300 miles
to see the kid...

246
00:17:04,974 --> 00:17:08,019
that's the greeting we get.
Come here, will ya?

247
00:17:09,395 --> 00:17:11,314
How ya doin' there?

248
00:17:11,356 --> 00:17:13,608
I'm sorry.
I'm really glad to see you...

249
00:17:13,650 --> 00:17:15,443
but I wish
I knew you were coming.

250
00:17:15,485 --> 00:17:16,736
I'll bet you did, huh?

251
00:17:16,819 --> 00:17:18,488
I looked for you
at that fraternity house.

252
00:17:18,530 --> 00:17:20,823
- They said you weren't a member.
- I can explain that.

253
00:17:20,907 --> 00:17:22,242
They also told me
you're not on the diving team.

254
00:17:22,283 --> 00:17:24,327
They said you were
the towel boy.

255
00:17:24,369 --> 00:17:26,704
- I can explain that, too.
- OK, explain it.

256
00:17:26,746 --> 00:17:29,582
- I lied.
- Great. That explains it, huh?

257
00:17:29,624 --> 00:17:32,752
Jason, you don't lie to me.
You lie to girls.

258
00:17:34,212 --> 00:17:35,338
Who's this?

259
00:17:35,380 --> 00:17:37,507
Oh, I'm sorry.
This is my roommate.

260
00:17:37,542 --> 00:17:38,508
That's Derek Lutz.

261
00:17:38,550 --> 00:17:41,261
This is the dad,
and that's Lou.

262
00:17:41,302 --> 00:17:43,763
- Is that your real hair?
- What do you think?

263
00:17:43,805 --> 00:17:46,933
I think you're trying
to get back at your parents.

264
00:17:46,968 --> 00:17:49,060
Show me the campus.
I want to talk to you.

265
00:17:49,102 --> 00:17:50,270
Oh, good.

266
00:17:58,027 --> 00:18:00,071
Boy, what a great-lookin' place.

267
00:18:00,113 --> 00:18:01,865
When I used to dream
about going to college...

268
00:18:01,906 --> 00:18:03,498
this is the way
I always pictured it.

269
00:18:03,533 --> 00:18:05,618
Wait a minute. When did you
dream about going to college?

270
00:18:05,702 --> 00:18:08,997
When I used to fall asleep
in high school.

271
00:18:09,038 --> 00:18:10,957
Dad, I know how much
all this means to you...

272
00:18:10,999 --> 00:18:14,377
- and I'm sorry I lied to you.
- You don't have to lie to me.

273
00:18:14,419 --> 00:18:16,921
No matter what you do,
I'll love you just the same.

274
00:18:16,963 --> 00:18:18,339
Will you love me
no matter what?

275
00:18:18,381 --> 00:18:19,549
No matter what.

276
00:18:19,591 --> 00:18:22,343
- I'm droppin' out.
- You're droppin' out?

277
00:18:22,378 --> 00:18:24,929
You just got here.
You just started.

278
00:18:24,971 --> 00:18:26,931
I know,
but I'm not making it here.

279
00:18:26,973 --> 00:18:29,225
I don't fit in, you know?
I got one friend... Derek.

280
00:18:29,267 --> 00:18:31,227
He's got no friends.

281
00:18:31,269 --> 00:18:33,771
The girls don't like me,
the fraternities don't want me.

282
00:18:33,813 --> 00:18:35,398
The diving coach
won't even talk to me.

283
00:18:35,440 --> 00:18:37,483
Look at it this way...

284
00:18:37,525 --> 00:18:39,485
at least you're getting
an education.

285
00:18:39,527 --> 00:18:42,071
Dad, last semester
I got nothing but "Cs. "

286
00:18:42,113 --> 00:18:43,907
A, B, C...
you're in the top three.

287
00:18:43,948 --> 00:18:45,533
What are you worrying about?

288
00:18:45,617 --> 00:18:47,368
I just think I'd be
a lot better off...

289
00:18:47,452 --> 00:18:49,037
gettin' a job or something.

290
00:18:49,078 --> 00:18:51,414
You never went to college.
Look how great you're doin'.

291
00:18:51,456 --> 00:18:54,042
Jason, I said it before
and I'll say it again.

292
00:18:54,083 --> 00:18:56,294
I don't care how rich
and successful a man is.

293
00:18:56,336 --> 00:18:57,921
Without an education,
he's nothing.

294
00:18:57,962 --> 00:19:00,298
I mean, stay in school.
Study harder.

295
00:19:00,340 --> 00:19:02,217
You can be whatever
you want to be.

296
00:19:02,258 --> 00:19:03,760
You want to be a loser,
be a loser.

297
00:19:03,801 --> 00:19:04,886
You want to be a winner,
be a winner.

298
00:19:04,928 --> 00:19:07,138
Jason, it's up to you.
You can do it.

299
00:19:07,180 --> 00:19:10,099
Remember, you're a Melon!

300
00:19:10,141 --> 00:19:14,270
Dad, that's easy for you to say.
You don't have to do any of it.

301
00:19:16,606 --> 00:19:18,900
OK, then.
I'll do it with you.

302
00:19:20,276 --> 00:19:21,736
What do you mean,
you'll do it with me?

303
00:19:21,778 --> 00:19:24,197
I mean just what I said.

304
00:19:24,239 --> 00:19:26,199
I'm going to college.
What do you think?

305
00:19:26,241 --> 00:19:28,701
What do I think?
I think you're nuts.

306
00:19:28,743 --> 00:19:32,539
Nuts, huh? Who made the rules?
Come here. I'm going to college!

307
00:19:32,580 --> 00:19:34,082
I'm going to college!

308
00:19:37,001 --> 00:19:39,587
Let me get this straight,
Mr. Melon.

309
00:19:39,671 --> 00:19:43,174
You wish to enter
this widely esteemed...

310
00:19:43,216 --> 00:19:45,677
Grand Lakes University of ours
as a freshman?

311
00:19:45,718 --> 00:19:47,512
That's right, Dean Martin.

312
00:19:48,680 --> 00:19:52,141
- Are you comfortable?
- I'm fine, yeah.

313
00:19:52,183 --> 00:19:54,269
Oh, the chair. I'm sorry.

314
00:19:57,313 --> 00:20:00,149
This is an awkward moment
for me, Mr. Melon...

315
00:20:00,191 --> 00:20:02,527
since I realize you're
a highly respected member...

316
00:20:02,569 --> 00:20:04,112
of our business community.

317
00:20:04,153 --> 00:20:06,948
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

318
00:20:06,990 --> 00:20:10,577
Our student body here
is handpicked by me...

319
00:20:10,618 --> 00:20:12,078
from the crème de la crème...

320
00:20:12,120 --> 00:20:15,248
of students all across
this great land of ours.

321
00:20:15,290 --> 00:20:17,292
That's one of the things
I like about this place.

322
00:20:17,333 --> 00:20:19,377
Yes. The point is, though...

323
00:20:19,419 --> 00:20:21,379
since you have
no high school diploma...

324
00:20:21,421 --> 00:20:24,841
and no transcripts of any kind,
no S.A.T. Scores...

325
00:20:24,883 --> 00:20:28,595
and you're 30 to 40 years older
than our average freshman...

326
00:20:28,636 --> 00:20:31,389
how can this university
ever see its way clear...

327
00:20:31,431 --> 00:20:33,808
to accept you as a student?

328
00:20:33,850 --> 00:20:36,436
As Calvin Coolidge once said...

329
00:20:36,477 --> 00:20:39,522
"The business of America
is business"...

330
00:20:39,564 --> 00:20:42,025
and the business of
an educational institution...

331
00:20:42,060 --> 00:20:44,694
such as ours
is to create young minds...

332
00:20:44,736 --> 00:20:46,654
that understand that
the business of America...

333
00:20:46,696 --> 00:20:50,331
is the kind of business
that it actually is.

334
00:20:50,366 --> 00:20:54,412
So, whatever it is that
I have said here today...

335
00:20:54,454 --> 00:20:59,083
the point is
that we are here to honor...

336
00:20:59,125 --> 00:21:02,212
our most generous benefactor...

337
00:21:02,253 --> 00:21:05,006
and newest freshman...

338
00:21:05,048 --> 00:21:06,799
the man who's
made it possible...

339
00:21:06,841 --> 00:21:09,719
for us to break ground
here today...

340
00:21:09,761 --> 00:21:12,096
Mr. Thornton Melon.

341
00:21:15,266 --> 00:21:17,560
Dean Martin, great speech.

342
00:21:17,602 --> 00:21:19,979
There's nothing like good,
clean business, huh?

343
00:21:20,021 --> 00:21:23,066
And a little monkey business.

344
00:21:23,107 --> 00:21:26,361
Oh, Philip. I'm so glad
you could make it.

345
00:21:26,402 --> 00:21:28,780
Mr. Melon, I'd like for you
to meet Dr. Philip Barbay...

346
00:21:28,821 --> 00:21:32,867
who's the dean
of our school of business.

347
00:21:32,909 --> 00:21:34,702
David, I just want
to get it on record...

348
00:21:34,744 --> 00:21:36,287
that I am totally against this.

349
00:21:36,329 --> 00:21:38,498
I don't think
that selling admission...

350
00:21:38,540 --> 00:21:40,583
to an obviously
unqualified student...

351
00:21:40,625 --> 00:21:43,127
is very ethical or honorable.

352
00:21:43,169 --> 00:21:46,714
Right, Phil,
but I'd just like to say...

353
00:21:46,756 --> 00:21:49,050
in all fairness
to Mr. Melon here...

354
00:21:49,092 --> 00:21:52,053
it was a really big check.

355
00:21:52,095 --> 00:21:54,180
It's a simple matter
of this man's presence...

356
00:21:54,222 --> 00:21:57,183
undermining the efforts
of our legitimate students...

357
00:21:57,225 --> 00:21:59,227
who are here as a result
of hard work.

358
00:21:59,262 --> 00:22:00,520
Hard work?

359
00:22:00,562 --> 00:22:03,314
Listen, Sherlock, while you were
tucked away up here...

360
00:22:03,356 --> 00:22:05,316
working on your ethics,
I was out there...

361
00:22:05,358 --> 00:22:07,360
busting my hump
in the real world.

362
00:22:07,402 --> 00:22:09,571
And the reason guys like you
got a place to teach...

363
00:22:09,612 --> 00:22:12,260
is 'cause guys like me
donate buildings.

364
00:22:12,295 --> 00:22:14,909
I wasn't speaking to you,
Mr. Melon.

365
00:22:21,958 --> 00:22:24,523
I don't think
Dr. Barbay understands...

366
00:22:24,558 --> 00:22:27,088
the actual amounts
that are involved here.

367
00:22:27,130 --> 00:22:31,342
Mr. Melon, will you take
the ceremonial shovel?

368
00:22:31,384 --> 00:22:32,343
Thank you.

369
00:22:32,385 --> 00:22:35,263
And dig into the symbolic dirt.

370
00:22:37,891 --> 00:22:42,896
I hereby dedicate
this building to... myself.

371
00:22:55,074 --> 00:22:57,076
Now, Dad, it's just like
we talked about.

372
00:22:57,118 --> 00:22:59,078
You sign up for whatever
interests you, OK?

373
00:22:59,120 --> 00:23:00,788
We're gonna get
on the astronomy line...

374
00:23:00,830 --> 00:23:02,832
before it closes up.
See you later.

375
00:23:04,667 --> 00:23:08,630
Look at this.
This is worse than the track.

376
00:23:08,671 --> 00:23:10,298
You want me to move
some people for you?

377
00:23:10,340 --> 00:23:11,382
No, don't push anybody around.

378
00:23:11,424 --> 00:23:14,010
This is college.
Let me think for a minute.

379
00:23:14,052 --> 00:23:15,637
What are you gonna do?

380
00:23:15,678 --> 00:23:18,056
Come on. I got an idea.

381
00:23:18,097 --> 00:23:19,057
Did you get
everything you want?

382
00:23:19,098 --> 00:23:21,809
I got the Latin
and the Sanskrit...

383
00:23:21,851 --> 00:23:23,519
but then they canceled
my Ancient Greek.

384
00:23:23,561 --> 00:23:25,521
Just blew my whole
dead languages motif.

385
00:23:25,563 --> 00:23:27,690
What are you looking at?

386
00:23:41,496 --> 00:23:43,957
You OK?

387
00:23:43,998 --> 00:23:47,502
Yeah. Yeah, I'm fine.

388
00:23:48,644 --> 00:23:51,021
I'm just upset
because they closed botany.

389
00:23:51,063 --> 00:23:53,023
Those bastards!

390
00:23:53,065 --> 00:23:55,233
Well, I'm not that upset.

391
00:23:56,568 --> 00:23:59,321
At least, I won't be
if I get into astronomy.

392
00:23:59,363 --> 00:24:01,657
You want to cut
into line with us?

393
00:24:01,698 --> 00:24:02,741
'Cause we're already waiting.

394
00:24:02,783 --> 00:24:05,619
Yes. Yeah, I would.

395
00:24:05,661 --> 00:24:06,745
Great. All right.

396
00:24:10,666 --> 00:24:12,542
Oh, this is Derek.

397
00:24:12,584 --> 00:24:15,420
Hi.

398
00:24:15,462 --> 00:24:17,214
I'm Valerie Desmond.

399
00:24:17,255 --> 00:24:19,257
Yeah, I know.

400
00:24:20,634 --> 00:24:23,595
- I'm Jason Melon.
- Hi.

401
00:24:27,683 --> 00:24:29,893
- Hey, Valerie.
- Hi.

402
00:24:29,935 --> 00:24:31,395
God, you look great.

403
00:24:31,436 --> 00:24:34,022
Thanks. Are you taking
astronomy, too?

404
00:24:34,064 --> 00:24:35,983
Yeah, I guess so.

405
00:24:36,024 --> 00:24:38,068
I don't really want to.
I'm a business major.

406
00:24:38,110 --> 00:24:41,154
But for some reason,
they want us to take a science.

407
00:24:41,196 --> 00:24:43,156
You mind if I sneak
in the line with you?

408
00:24:43,198 --> 00:24:46,118
Actually, these guys were
nice enough to let me in...

409
00:24:46,153 --> 00:24:49,538
so it's really
up to them, I guess.

410
00:24:49,579 --> 00:24:51,331
Melon, buddy?

411
00:24:51,373 --> 00:24:53,834
Whaddaya say? Let me in, OK?

412
00:24:53,875 --> 00:24:56,378
I don't think so, Osbourne.

413
00:24:56,420 --> 00:24:58,463
Melon, your friend...
straighten him out.

414
00:24:58,505 --> 00:25:00,048
Look, Chas,
there's a lot of people waiting.

415
00:25:00,090 --> 00:25:02,718
It wouldn't really be fair.

416
00:25:02,759 --> 00:25:03,844
I'll tell you what.

417
00:25:03,885 --> 00:25:07,973
Maybe if you got a note
from each of these people...

418
00:25:08,015 --> 00:25:10,142
saying that it was all right,
then we'd reconsider...

419
00:25:10,183 --> 00:25:12,019
but until that day,
take a hike...

420
00:25:12,060 --> 00:25:15,147
you elitist fraternity scumbag.

421
00:25:18,817 --> 00:25:20,861
I won't forget this, Melon.

422
00:25:20,902 --> 00:25:22,696
I'll see you at the pool.

423
00:25:22,738 --> 00:25:24,072
- Bye, Val.
- Bye.

424
00:25:24,114 --> 00:25:25,706
Thank you. I'm dead.

425
00:25:25,741 --> 00:25:27,743
You're not gonna believe this!

426
00:25:27,784 --> 00:25:30,370
- You're kidding!
- I'm not kidding! Just go!

427
00:25:30,412 --> 00:25:32,080
He's out there!

428
00:25:42,299 --> 00:25:45,636
Bruce! Bruce! Bruce! Bruce!

429
00:25:50,599 --> 00:25:51,933
Where is he?

430
00:25:51,975 --> 00:25:53,101
I don't know, kid.

431
00:25:53,185 --> 00:25:54,895
All I know is I'm supposed
to pick him up here.

432
00:25:54,930 --> 00:25:56,897
- When?
- Now.

433
00:25:56,938 --> 00:25:59,608
Come on, let's register.

434
00:26:08,283 --> 00:26:09,826
Hey, you guys
get everything you need?

435
00:26:09,868 --> 00:26:11,119
Oh, yeah, we got it.

436
00:26:11,161 --> 00:26:12,746
Good. What's with
the used books?

437
00:26:12,788 --> 00:26:15,207
- What's wrong with used books?
- They've already been read.

438
00:26:15,248 --> 00:26:17,042
And they've already been
underlined.

439
00:26:17,084 --> 00:26:18,293
That's the problem.

440
00:26:18,335 --> 00:26:20,587
The guy who underlined them
could have been a maniac.

441
00:26:20,671 --> 00:26:23,966
Get these guys some new books.

442
00:26:24,007 --> 00:26:26,927
Charge it to me, too.
Here, pick a card.

443
00:26:28,136 --> 00:26:30,931
And I'm taking four
of those school sweaters...

444
00:26:30,973 --> 00:26:33,600
a bunch of pennants,
some of those beer mugs...

445
00:26:33,642 --> 00:26:36,269
a few of these fuzz balls
you cheer with, and...

446
00:26:36,311 --> 00:26:39,564
Hey, folks, it's on me!
Shakespeare for everyone, OK?

447
00:26:41,149 --> 00:26:44,111
You, too, honey.
I'd like to tame your shrew.

448
00:26:44,152 --> 00:26:47,990
- Who is that?
- That is Mr. Thornton Melon...

449
00:26:48,031 --> 00:26:50,659
the world's oldest
living freshman...

450
00:26:50,701 --> 00:26:53,745
and the walking epitome of
the decline of modern education.

451
00:26:53,787 --> 00:26:56,164
The stupid clod thinks he can
buy his way out of the gutter.

452
00:26:56,206 --> 00:26:58,507
I don't think so.
He was just having fun.

453
00:26:58,542 --> 00:27:03,213
Oh, really? Well, I can't wait
to get him in my class.

454
00:27:03,255 --> 00:27:05,382
We'll see how much fun
he is then.

455
00:27:05,424 --> 00:27:06,633
Oh, Philip.

456
00:27:06,675 --> 00:27:09,678
Hey, Mr. M! You're all set.
We've been working all night.

457
00:27:09,720 --> 00:27:11,263
We got it all done.

458
00:27:11,305 --> 00:27:13,140
Thanks, Buzzy.
I appreciate it.

459
00:27:13,181 --> 00:27:16,435
Add a few hundred to the bill
and throw your boys a party.

460
00:27:16,476 --> 00:27:19,604
You know what you got, Mr. M?
You got class.

461
00:27:19,646 --> 00:27:22,858
It rubbed off from you, Buzzy.
Say hello to Sonia for me, huh?

462
00:27:22,899 --> 00:27:24,109
You got it.

463
00:27:24,151 --> 00:27:27,029
I want to talk to you
about my schedule.

464
00:27:27,070 --> 00:27:29,239
We'll go over it later.

465
00:27:42,044 --> 00:27:44,421
Well, boys,
what do you think?

466
00:27:44,456 --> 00:27:46,340
Got a hot tub in there!

467
00:27:46,381 --> 00:27:48,550
How can you study
if you're not relaxed?

468
00:27:48,592 --> 00:27:49,676
When's our first class?

469
00:27:49,718 --> 00:27:51,887
We got economics
tomorrow at 11:00.

470
00:27:51,928 --> 00:27:53,096
11:00? No good.

471
00:27:53,138 --> 00:27:55,307
I got a massage at 11:00.
Tell them to make it 2:00.

472
00:27:55,390 --> 00:27:58,518
No, Dad, you don't get it.

473
00:27:58,560 --> 00:28:02,689
They're not gonna reschedule
the classes around your massage.

474
00:28:02,731 --> 00:28:05,233
All right, 11:00.
But I'm gonna talk to that dean.

475
00:28:05,275 --> 00:28:07,819
These classes can be
a real inconvenience.

476
00:28:07,861 --> 00:28:10,322
All right, settle down, people.

477
00:28:10,364 --> 00:28:13,367
We've got a lot to cover,
and time is short.

478
00:28:17,162 --> 00:28:20,207
There are two kinds of people
in business today...

479
00:28:20,248 --> 00:28:22,209
the quick and the dead.

480
00:28:22,250 --> 00:28:25,379
So, rather than waste
your time this semester...

481
00:28:25,420 --> 00:28:27,839
with a lot of
useless theories...

482
00:28:27,923 --> 00:28:29,883
we're going to jump right in
with both feet...

483
00:28:29,925 --> 00:28:32,844
and create a fictional company
from the ground up.

484
00:28:32,886 --> 00:28:35,889
We'll construct
our physical plant...

485
00:28:35,931 --> 00:28:38,392
we'll set up
an efficient administrative...

486
00:28:38,433 --> 00:28:40,227
and executive structure...

